# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: critical-phenomena
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] In statistical mechanics, the **correlation function** is a measure of the order in a system, as characterized by a mathematical correlation function.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Correlation functions describe how microscopic variables, such as spin and density, at different positions or times are related.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] More specifically, correlation functions measure quantitatively the extent to which microscopic variables fluctuate together, on average, across space and/or time.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Keep in mind that correlation doesn't automatically equate to causation.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] So, even if there's a non-zero correlation between two points in space or time, it doesn't mean there is a direct causal link between them.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Sometimes, a correlation can exist without any causal relationship.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] This could be purely coincidental or due to other underlying factors, known as confounding variables, which cause both points to covary (statistically).
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] A classic example of spatial correlation can be seen in ferromagnetic and antiferromagnetic materials.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] In these materials, atomic spins tend to align in parallel and antiparallel configurations with their adjacent counterparts, respectively.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] The figure on the right visually represents this spatial correlation between spins in such materials.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Here the brackets, $\langle \cdot \rangle$ , indicate the above-mentioned thermal average.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] It is important to note here, however, that while the brackets are called an average, they are calculated as an expected value, not an average value.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Correlation functions between the same random variable are autocorrelation functions.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] However, in statistical mechanics, not all correlation functions are autocorrelation functions.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] For example, in multicomponent condensed phases, the pair correlation function between different elements is often of interest.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Such mixed-element pair correlation functions are an example of cross-correlation functions, as the random variables $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ represent the average variations in density as a function position for two distinct elements.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Often, one is interested in solely the *spatial* influence of a given random variable, say the direction of a spin, on its local environment, without considering later times, $\tau$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] In this case, we neglect the time evolution of the system, so the above definition is re-written with $\tau =0$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] This defines the **equal-time correlation function**, $C(r,0)$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] The Radial distribution function is an example of an equal-time correlation function where the uncorrelated reference is generally not subtracted.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Other equal-time spin-spin correlation functions are shown on this page for a variety of materials and conditions.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] One might also be interested in the *temporal* evolution of microscopic variables.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] In other words, how the value of a microscopic variable at a given position and time, R and t , influences the value of the same microscopic variable at a later time, $t+\tau$ (and usually at the same position).
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Such temporal correlations are quantified via **equal-position correlation functions**, $C(0,\tau )$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] The above assumption may seem non-intuitive at first: how can an ensemble which is time-invariant have a non-uniform temporal correlation function?
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Temporal correlations remain relevant to talk about in equilibrium systems because a time-invariant, *macroscopic* ensemble can still have non-trivial temporal dynamics *microscopically*.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] A single-phase system at equilibrium has a homogeneous composition macroscopically.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] However, if one watches the microscopic movement of each atom, fluctuations in composition are constantly occurring due to the quasi-random walks taken by the individual atoms.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Statistical mechanics allows one to make insightful statements about the temporal behavior of such fluctuations of equilibrium systems.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] This is discussed below in the section on the temporal evolution of correlation functions and Onsager's regression hypothesis.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Time correlation function plays a significant role in nonequilibrium statistical mechanics as partition function does in equilibrium statistical mechanics.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] For instance, transport coefficients are closely related to time correlation functions through the Fourier transform; and the Green-Kubo relations, used to calculate relaxation and dissipation processes in a system, are expressed in terms of equilibrium time correlation functions.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] The time correlation function of two observables A and B is defined as, $C_{AB}(t_{1},t_{2})=\langle A(t_{1})B(t_{2})\rangle$ and this definition applies for both classical and quantum version.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] For stationary (equilibrium) system, the time origin is irrelevant, and $C_{AB}(\tau )=C_{AB}(t_{1},t_{2})$ , with $\tau =t_{2}-t_{1}$ as the time difference.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] As $t\to 0$ , the correlation function $C_{AB}(0)=\langle AB\rangle$ , while as $t\to \infty$ , we may assume the correlation vanishes and $\lim _{t\to \infty }C_{AB}(t)=\langle A\rangle \langle B\rangle$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Nevertheless, semiclassical initial value representation (SC-IVR) is a family to evaluate the quantum time correlation function from the definition.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Additionally, there are two alternative quantum time correlations, and they both related to the definition of quantum time correlation function in the Fourier space.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Quantum time correlation function can be approximated using the path integral molecular dynamics.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] All of the above correlation functions have been defined in the context of equilibrium statistical mechanics.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] However, it is possible to define correlation functions for systems away from equilibrium.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Examining the general definition of $C(r,\tau )$ , it is clear that one can define the random variables used in these correlation functions, such as atomic positions and spins, away from equilibrium.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] As such, their scalar product is well-defined away from equilibrium.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] The operation which is no longer well-defined away from equilibrium is the average over the equilibrium ensemble.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] This averaging process for non-equilibrium system is typically replaced by averaging the scalar product across the entire sample.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] This is typical in scattering experiments and computer simulations, and is often used to measure the radial distribution functions of glasses.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] One can also define averages over states for systems perturbed slightly from equilibrium.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Correlation functions are typically measured with scattering experiments.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] For example, x-ray scattering experiments directly measure electron-electron equal-time correlations.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] From knowledge of elemental structure factors, one can also measure elemental pair correlation functions.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] See Radial distribution function for further information.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Equal-time spin–spin correlation functions are measured with neutron scattering as opposed to x-ray scattering.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Neutron scattering can also yield information on pair correlations as well.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] For systems composed of particles larger than about one micrometer, optical microscopy can be used to measure both equal-time and equal-position correlation functions.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Optical microscopy is thus common for colloidal suspensions, especially in two dimensions.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] In 1931, Lars Onsager proposed that the regression of microscopic thermal fluctuations at equilibrium follows the macroscopic law of relaxation of small non-equilibrium disturbances.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] This is known as the *Onsager regression hypothesis*.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Equilibrium fluctuations of the system can be related to its response to external perturbations via the Fluctuation-dissipation theorem.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Continuous phase transitions, such as order-disorder transitions in metallic alloys and ferromagnetic-paramagnetic transitions, involve a transition from an ordered to a disordered state.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] In terms of correlation functions, the equal-time correlation function is non-zero for all lattice points below the critical temperature, and is non-negligible for only a fairly small radius above the critical temperature.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] As the phase transition is continuous, the length over which the microscopic variables are correlated, $\xi$ , must transition continuously from being infinite to finite when the material is heated through its critical temperature.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] This gives rise to a power-law dependence of the correlation function as a function of distance at the critical point.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] This is shown in the figure in the left for the case of a ferromagnetic material, with the quantitative details listed in the section on magnetism.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] In a spin system, the equal-time correlation function is especially well-studied.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Schematic plots of this function are shown for a ferromagnetic material below, at, and above its Curie temperature on the left.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Even in a magnetically disordered phase, spins at different positions are correlated, i.e., if the distance r is very small (compared to some length scale $\xi$ ), the interaction between the spins will cause them to be correlated.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] The alignment that would naturally arise as a result of the interaction between spins is destroyed by thermal effects.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] where r is the distance between spins, and d is the dimension of the system, and $\vartheta$ is an exponent, whose value depends on whether the system is in the disordered phase (i.e. above the critical point), or in the ordered phase (i.e. below the critical point).
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] At high temperatures, the correlation decays to zero exponentially with the distance between the spins.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] The same exponential decay as a function of radial distance is also observed below $T_{c}$ , but with the limit at large distances being the mean magnetization $\langle M^{2}\rangle$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] where $\eta$ is a critical exponent, which does not have any simple relation with the non-critical exponent $\vartheta$ introduced above.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] For example, the exact solution of the two-dimensional Ising model (with short-ranged ferromagnetic interactions) gives precisely at criticality $\eta ={\frac {1}{4}}$ , but above criticality $\vartheta ={\frac {1}{2}}$ and below criticality $\vartheta =2$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] This power law correlation is responsible for the scaling, seen in these transitions.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] All exponents mentioned are independent of temperature.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] They are in fact universal, i.e. found to be the same in a wide variety of systems.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] One common correlation function is the radial distribution function which is seen often in statistical mechanics and fluid mechanics.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] The correlation function can be calculated in exactly solvable models (one-dimensional Bose gas, spin chains, Hubbard model) by means of Quantum inverse scattering method and Bethe ansatz.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] In an isotropic XY model, time and temperature correlations were evaluated by Its, Korepin, Izergin & Slavnov.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] However, such higher order correlation functions are relatively difficult to interpret and measure.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] For example, in order to measure the higher-order analogues of pair distribution functions, coherent x-ray sources are needed.
[src:critical-phenomena/correlation-function-statistical-mechanics] Both the theory of such analysis and the experimental measurement of the needed X-ray cross-correlation functions are areas of active research.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] These properties of critical exponents are supported by experimental data.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Analytical results can be theoretically achieved in mean field theory in high dimensions or when exact solutions are known such as the two-dimensional Ising model.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The theoretical treatment in generic dimensions requires the renormalization group approach or, for systems at thermal equilibrium, the conformal bootstrap techniques.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Phase transitions and critical exponents appear in many physical systems such as water at the critical point, in magnetic systems, in superconductivity, in percolation and in turbulent fluids.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The critical dimension above which mean field exponents are valid varies with the systems and can even be infinite.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The control parameter that drives phase transitions is often temperature but can also be other macroscopic variables like pressure or an external magnetic field.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] For simplicity, the following discussion works in terms of temperature; the translation to another control parameter is straightforward.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The temperature at which the transition occurs is called the critical temperature *T*c.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] It is important to remember that this represents the asymptotic behavior of the function *f*(*τ*) as *τ* → 0.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Let us assume that the system at thermal equilibrium has two different phases characterized by an order parameter *Ψ*, which vanishes at and above *T*c.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Consider the disordered phase (*τ* > 0), ordered phase (*τ* < 0) and critical temperature (*τ* = 0) phases separately.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Following the standard convention, the critical exponents related to the ordered phase are primed.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] It is also another standard convention to use superscript/subscript + (−) for the disordered (ordered) state.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] In general spontaneous symmetry breaking occurs in the ordered phase.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The critical exponents can be derived from the specific free energy *f*(*J*,*T*) as a function of the source and temperature.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The correlation length can be derived from the functional *F*[*J*;*T*].
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] In many cases, the critical exponents defined in the ordered and disordered phases are identical.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] When the upper critical dimension is four, these relations are accurate close to the critical point in two- and three-dimensional systems.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] In four dimensions, however, the power laws are modified by logarithmic factors.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] These do not appear in dimensions arbitrarily close to but not exactly four, which can be used as a way around this problem.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] One of the major discoveries in the study of critical phenomena is that mean field theory of critical points is only correct when the space dimension of the system is higher than a certain dimension called the upper critical dimension which excludes the physical dimensions 1, 2 or 3 in most cases.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The problem with mean field theory is that the critical exponents do not depend on the space dimension.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] This leads to a quantitative discrepancy below the critical dimensions, where the true critical exponents differ from the mean field values.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] It can even lead to a qualitative discrepancy at low space dimension, where a critical point in fact can no longer exist, even though mean field theory still predicts there is one.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] This is the case for the Ising model in dimension 1 where there is no phase transition.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The space dimension where mean field theory becomes qualitatively incorrect is called the lower critical dimension.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The most accurately measured value of *α* is −0.0127(3) for the phase transition of superfluid helium (the so-called lambda transition).
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The value was measured on a space shuttle to minimize pressure differences in the sample.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] This value is in a significant disagreement with the most precise theoretical determinations coming from high temperature expansion techniques, Monte Carlo methods and the conformal bootstrap.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Critical exponents can be evaluated via Monte Carlo methods of lattice models.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The accuracy of this first principle method depends on the available computational resources, which determine the ability to go to the infinite volume limit and to reduce statistical errors.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Other techniques rely on theoretical understanding of critical fluctuations.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The most widely applicable technique is the renormalization group.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The conformal bootstrap is a more recently developed technique, which has achieved unsurpassed accuracy for the Ising critical exponents.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] In light of the critical scalings, we can reexpress all thermodynamic quantities in terms of dimensionless quantities.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Close enough to the critical point, everything can be reexpressed in terms of certain ratios of the powers of the reduced quantities.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The origin of scaling functions can be seen from the renormalization group.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The critical point is an infrared fixed point.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] In a sufficiently small neighborhood of the critical point, we may linearize the action of the renormalization group.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] This basically means that rescaling the system by a factor of *a* will be equivalent to rescaling operators and source fields by a factor of *a**Δ* for some *Δ*.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] So, we may reparameterize all quantities in terms of rescaled scale independent quantities.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] It was believed for a long time that the critical exponents were the same above and below the critical temperature, e.g.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] It has now been shown that this is not necessarily true: When a continuous symmetry is explicitly broken down to a discrete symmetry by irrelevant (in the renormalization group sense) anisotropies, then the exponents *γ* and *γ*′ are not identical.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Critical exponents are denoted by Greek letters.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] These equations imply that there are only two independent exponents, e.g., *ν* and *η*.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] All this follows from the theory of the renormalization group.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Phase transitions and critical exponents also appear in percolation processes where the concentration of "occupied" sites or links of a lattice are the control parameter of the phase transition (compared to temperature in classical phase transitions in physics).
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] One of the simplest examples is Bernoulli percolation in a two dimensional square lattice.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Sites are randomly occupied with probability p .
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] A cluster is defined as a collection of nearest neighbouring occupied sites.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] For small values of p the occupied sites form only small local clusters.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] At the percolation threshold $p_{c}\approx 0.5927$ (also called critical probability) a spanning cluster that extends across opposite sites of the system is formed, and we have a second-order phase transition that is characterized by universal critical exponents.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] For percolation the universality class is different from the Ising universality class.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] For example, the correlation length critical exponent is $\nu =4/3$ for 2D Bernoulli percolation compared to $\nu =1$ for the 2D Ising model.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] There are some anisotropic systems where the correlation length is direction dependent.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Directed percolation can be also regarded as anisotropic percolation.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] In this case the critical exponents are different and the upper critical dimension is 5.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] More complex behavior may occur at multicritical points, at the border or on intersections of critical manifolds.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] They can be reached by tuning the value of two or more parameters, such as temperature and pressure.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The above examples exclusively refer to the static properties of a critical system.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] However dynamic properties of the system may become critical, too.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Especially, the characteristic time, *τ*char, of a system diverges as *τ*char ∝ *ξ z*, with a *dynamical exponent* *z*.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Moreover, the large *static universality classes* of equivalent models with identical static critical exponents decompose into smaller *dynamical universality classes*, if one demands that also the dynamical exponents are identical.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] The equilibrium critical exponents can be computed from conformal field theory.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-exponent] Critical exponents also exist for self organized criticality for dissipative systems.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] In physics, **critical phenomena** is the collective name associated with the physics of critical points.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Most of them stem from the divergence of the correlation length, but also the dynamics slows down.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Critical phenomena include scaling relations among different quantities, power-law divergences of some quantities (such as the magnetic susceptibility in the ferromagnetic phase transition) described by critical exponents, universality, fractal behaviour, and ergodicity breaking.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Critical phenomena take place in second order phase transitions, although not exclusively.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] The critical behavior is usually different from the mean-field approximation which is valid away from the phase transition, since the latter neglects correlations, which become increasingly important as the system approaches the critical point where the correlation length diverges.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Many properties of the critical behavior of a system can be derived in the framework of the renormalization group.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] In order to explain the physical origin of these phenomena, we shall use the Ising model as a pedagogical example.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] where the sum is extended over the pairs of nearest neighbours and J is a coupling constant, which we will consider to be fixed.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] There is a certain temperature, called the Curie temperature or critical temperature, $T_{c}$ below which the system presents ferromagnetic long range order.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Above it, it is paramagnetic and is apparently disordered.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] At temperature zero, the system may only take one global sign, either +1 or -1.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] At higher temperatures, but below $T_{c}$ , the state is still globally magnetized, but clusters of the opposite sign appear.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] As the temperature increases, these clusters start to contain smaller clusters themselves, in a typical Russian dolls picture.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Their typical size, called the correlation length, $\xi$ grows with temperature until it diverges at $T_{c}$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] This means that the whole system is such a cluster, and there is no global magnetization.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Above that temperature, the system is globally disordered, but with ordered clusters within it, whose size is again called *correlation length*, but it is now decreasing with temperature.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] At infinite temperature, it is again zero, with the system fully disordered.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] The correlation length diverges at the critical point: as $T\to T_{c}$ , $\xi \to \infty$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] This divergence poses no physical problem.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Other physical observables diverge at this point, leading to some confusion at the beginning.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Let us apply a very small magnetic field to the system in the critical point.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] A very small magnetic field is not able to magnetize a large coherent cluster, but with these fractal clusters the picture changes.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] It affects easily the smallest size clusters, since they have a nearly paramagnetic behaviour.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] But this change, in its turn, affects the next-scale clusters, and the perturbation climbs the ladder until the whole system changes radically.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Thus, critical systems are very sensitive to small changes in the environment.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Other observables, such as the specific heat, may also diverge at this point.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] All these divergences stem from that of the correlation length.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] As we approach the critical point, these diverging observables behave as $A(T)\propto (T-T_{c})^{\alpha }$ for some exponent $\alpha \,,$ where, typically, the value of the exponent α is the same above and below Tc.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] These exponents are called critical exponents and are robust observables.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Even more, they take the same values for very different physical systems.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] This intriguing phenomenon, called universality, is explained, qualitatively and also quantitatively, by the renormalization group.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Critical phenomena may also appear for *dynamic* quantities, not only for *static* ones.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] In fact, the divergence of the characteristic *time* $\tau$ of a system is directly related to the divergence of the thermal *correlation length* $\xi$ by the introduction of a dynamical exponent *z* and the relation $\tau =\xi ^{\,z}$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] The voluminous *static universality class* of a system splits into different, less voluminous *dynamic universality classes* with different values of *z* but a common static critical behaviour, and by approaching the critical point one may observe all kinds of slowing-down phenomena.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] The divergence of relaxation time $\tau$ at criticality leads to singularities in various collective transport quantities, e.g., the interdiffusivity, shear viscosity $\eta \sim \xi ^{x_{\eta }}$ , and bulk viscosity $\zeta \sim \xi ^{x_{\zeta }}$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] The dynamic critical exponents follow certain scaling relations, viz., $z=d+x_{\eta }$ , where d is the space dimension.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] There is only one independent dynamic critical exponent.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Values of these exponents are dictated by several universality classes.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] According to the Hohenberg−Halperin nomenclature, for the model H universality class (fluids) $x_{\eta }\simeq 0.068,z\simeq 3.068$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Ergodicity is the assumption that a system, at a given temperature, explores the full phase space, just each state takes different probabilities.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] In an Ising ferromagnet below $T_{c}$ this does not happen.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] If $T<T_{c}$ , never mind how close they are, the system has chosen a global magnetization, and the phase space is divided into two regions.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] From one of them it is impossible to reach the other, unless a magnetic field is applied, or temperature is raised above $T_{c}$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] In two-dimensional systems, conformal field theory is a powerful tool which has discovered many new properties of 2D critical systems, employing the fact that scale invariance, along with a few other requisites, leads to an infinite symmetry group.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] The critical point is described by a conformal field theory.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] According to the renormalization group theory, the defining property of criticality is that the characteristic length scale of the structure of the physical system, also known as the correlation length *ξ*, becomes infinite.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] This can happen along *critical lines* in phase space.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] This effect is the cause of the critical opalescence that can be observed as a binary fluid mixture approaches its liquid–liquid critical point.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] In systems in equilibrium, the critical point is reached only by precisely tuning a control parameter.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] However, in some non-equilibrium systems, the critical point is an attractor of the dynamics in a manner that is robust with respect to system parameters, a phenomenon referred to as self-organized criticality.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Applications arise in physics and chemistry, but also in fields such as sociology.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] For example, it is natural to describe a system of two political parties by an Ising model.
[src:critical-phenomena/critical-phenomena] Thereby, at a transition from one majority to the other, the above-mentioned critical phenomena may appear.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The **Ising model** (or **Lenz–Ising model**), named after the physicists Ernst Ising and Wilhelm Lenz, is a mathematical model of ferromagnetism in statistical mechanics.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The model consists of discrete variables that represent magnetic dipole moments of atomic "spins" that can be in one of two states (+1 or −1).
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The spins are arranged in a graph, usually a lattice (where the local structure repeats periodically in all directions), allowing each spin to interact with its neighbors.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Neighboring spins that agree have a lower energy than those that disagree; the system tends to the lowest energy but heat disturbs this tendency, thus creating the possibility of different structural phases.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The two-dimensional square-lattice Ising model is one of the simplest statistical models to show a phase transition.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Though it is a highly simplified model of a magnetic material, the Ising model can still provide qualitative and sometimes quantitative results applicable to real physical systems, and in general, it can be seen as a specialization of Stanley's *n*-vector model for *n* = 1.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The Ising model was invented by the physicist Wilhelm Lenz (1920), who gave it as a problem to his student Ernst Ising.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The one-dimensional Ising model was solved by Ising (1925) alone in his 1924 thesis; it has no phase transition.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The two-dimensional square-lattice Ising model is much harder and was only given an analytic description much later, by Lars Onsager (1944).
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] It is usually solved by a transfer-matrix method, although there exists a very simple approach relating the model to a non-interacting fermionic quantum field theory.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] In dimensions greater than four, the phase transition of the Ising model is described by mean-field theory.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The solution to this model exhibited a new, unusual phase transition behavior, along with non-vanishing long-range and nearest-neighbor spin-spin correlations, deemed relevant to large neural networks as one of its possible applications.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The Ising problem without an external field can be equivalently formulated as a graph maximum cut (Max-Cut) problem that can be solved via combinatorial optimization.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Consider a set $\Lambda$ of lattice sites, each with a set of adjacent sites (e.g. a graph) forming a d -dimensional lattice.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] For each lattice site $k\in \Lambda$ there is a discrete variable $\sigma _{k}$ such that $\sigma _{k}\in \{-1,+1\}$ , representing the site's spin.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] A *spin configuration*, ${\sigma }=\{\sigma _{k}\}_{k\in \Lambda }$ is an assignment of spin value to each lattice site.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] For any two adjacent sites $i,j\in \Lambda$ there is an *interaction* $J_{ij}$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Also a site $j\in \Lambda$ has an *external magnetic field* $h_{j}$ interacting with it.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] where the first sum is over pairs of adjacent spins (every pair is counted once).
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The notation $\langle ij\rangle$ indicates that sites i and j are nearest neighbors.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Note that the sign in the second term of the Hamiltonian above should actually be positive because the electron's magnetic moment is antiparallel to its spin, but the negative term is used conventionally.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The Ising Hamiltonian is an example of a pseudo-Boolean function; tools from the analysis of Boolean functions can be applied to describe and study it.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The configuration probabilities $P_{\beta }(\sigma )$ represent the probability that (in equilibrium) the system is in a state with configuration $\sigma$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The minus sign on each term of the Hamiltonian function $H(\sigma )$ is conventional.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The system is called ferromagnetic or antiferromagnetic if all interactions are ferromagnetic or all are antiferromagnetic.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The original Ising models were ferromagnetic, and it is still often assumed that "Ising model" means a ferromagnetic Ising model.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] In a ferromagnetic Ising model, spins desire to be aligned: the configurations in which adjacent spins are of the same sign have higher probability.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] In an antiferromagnetic model, adjacent spins tend to have opposite signs.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The sign convention of *H*(σ) also explains how a spin site *j* interacts with the external field.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Namely, the spin site wants to line up with the external field.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Ising models are often examined without an external field interacting with the lattice, that is, *h* = 0 for all *j* in the lattice Λ.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] When the external field is zero everywhere, *h* = 0, the Ising model is symmetric under switching the value of the spin in all the lattice sites; a nonzero field breaks this symmetry.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Another common simplification is to assume that all of the nearest neighbors ⟨*ij*⟩ have the same interaction strength.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Then we can set *Jij* = *J* for all pairs *i*, *j* in Λ.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] A subset S of the vertex set V(G) of a weighted undirected graph G determines a cut of the graph G into S and its complementary subset G\S.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The size of the cut is the sum of the weights of the edges between S and G\S.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] A maximum cut size is at least the size of any other cut, varying S.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Here each vertex i of the graph is a spin site that takes a spin value $\sigma _{i}=\pm 1$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] A given spin configuration $\sigma$ partitions the set of vertices $V(G)$ into two $\sigma$ -depended subsets, those with spin up $V^{+}$ and those with spin down $V^{-}$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] We denote by $\delta (V^{+})$ the $\sigma$ -depended set of edges that connects the two complementary vertex subsets $V^{+}$ and $V^{-}$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] where $W_{ij}$ denotes a weight of the edge $ij$ and the scaling 1/2 is introduced to compensate for double counting the same weights $W_{ij}=W_{ji}$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] where the total sum in the first term does not depend on $\sigma$ , imply that minimizing $H(\sigma )$ in $\sigma$ is equivalent to minimizing $\sum _{ij\in \delta (V^{+})}J_{ij}$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The most studied case of the Ising model is the translation-invariant ferromagnetic zero-field model on a *d*-dimensional lattice, namely, Λ = **Z***d*, *J**ij* = 1, *h* = 0.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] In his 1924 PhD thesis, Ising solved the model for the *d* = 1 case, which can be thought of as a linear horizontal lattice where each site only interacts with its left and right neighbor.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] In one dimension, the solution admits no phase transition.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] On the basis of this result, he incorrectly concluded that this model does not exhibit phase behaviour in any dimension.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The Ising model undergoes a phase transition between an ordered and a disordered phase in 2 dimensions or more.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This was first proven by Rudolf Peierls in 1936, using what is now called a **Peierls argument**.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The Ising model on a two-dimensional square lattice with no magnetic field was analytically solved by Lars Onsager (1944).
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Onsager obtained the correlation functions and free energy of the Ising model and announced the formula for the spontaneous magnetization for the 2-dimensional model in 1949 but did not give a derivation.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Yang (1952) gave the first published proof of this formula, using a limit formula for Fredholm determinants, proved in 1951 by Szegő in direct response to Onsager's work.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] A number of correlation inequalities have been derived rigorously for the Ising spin correlations (for general lattice structures), which have enabled mathematicians to study the Ising model both on and off criticality.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] where $\langle \sigma _{A}\rangle =\langle \prod _{j\in A}\sigma _{j}\rangle$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] With $B=\emptyset$ , the special case $\langle \sigma _{A}\rangle \geq 0$ results.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This means that spins are positively correlated on the Ising ferromagnet.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] An immediate application of this is that the magnetization of any set of spins $\langle \sigma _{A}\rangle$ is increasing with respect to any set of coupling constants $J_{B}$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This inequality can be used to establish the sharpness of phase transition for the Ising model.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This inequality is proven first for a type of positively-correlated percolation model, of which includes a representation of the Ising model.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] It is used to determine the critical temperatures of planar Potts model using percolation arguments (which includes the Ising model as a special case).
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] While the laws of chemical bonding made it clear to nineteenth century chemists that atoms were real, among physicists the debate continued well into the early twentieth century.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Atomists, notably James Clerk Maxwell and Ludwig Boltzmann, applied Hamilton's formulation of Newton's laws to large systems, and found that the statistical behavior of the atoms correctly describes room temperature gases.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] But classical statistical mechanics did not account for all of the properties of liquids and solids, nor of gases at low temperature.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Once modern quantum mechanics was formulated, atomism was no longer in conflict with experiment, but this did not lead to a universal acceptance of statistical mechanics, which went beyond atomism.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Josiah Willard Gibbs had given a complete formalism to reproduce the laws of thermodynamics from the laws of mechanics.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] But many faulty arguments survived from the 19th century, when statistical mechanics was considered dubious.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The lapses in intuition mostly stemmed from the fact that the limit of an infinite statistical system has many zero-one laws which are absent in finite systems: an infinitesimal change in a parameter can lead to big differences in the overall, aggregate behavior.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The exponential function is everywhere analytic as a function of β.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The sum of analytic functions is an analytic function.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This argument works for a finite sum of exponentials, and correctly establishes that there are no singularities in the free energy of a system of a finite size.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] For systems which are in the thermodynamic limit (that is, for infinite systems) the infinite sum can lead to singularities.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The convergence to the thermodynamic limit is fast, so that the phase behavior is apparent already on a relatively small lattice, even though the singularities are smoothed out by the system's finite size.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This was first established by Rudolf Peierls in the Ising model.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Shortly after Lenz and Ising constructed the Ising model, Peierls was able to explicitly show that a phase transition occurs in two dimensions.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] To do this, he compared the high-temperature and low-temperature limits.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] At infinite temperature (β = 0) all configurations have equal probability.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Each spin is completely independent of any other, and if typical configurations at infinite temperature are plotted so that plus/minus are represented by black and white, they look like television snow.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] For high, but not infinite temperature, there are small correlations between neighboring positions, the snow tends to clump a little bit, but the screen stays randomly looking, and there is no net excess of black or white.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] A bogus argument analogous to the argument in the last section now establishes that the *average* magnetization in the Ising model is always zero.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] So for every configuration with magnetization *M* there is a configuration with magnetization −*M* with equal probability.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The system should therefore spend equal amounts of time in the configuration with magnetization *M* as with magnetization −*M*.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] So the average magnetization (over all time) is zero.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] As before, this only proves that the average magnetization is zero at any finite volume.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] For an infinite system, fluctuations might not be able to push the system from a mostly plus state to a mostly minus with a nonzero probability.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] For very high temperatures, the magnetization is zero, as it is at infinite temperature.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] To see this, note that if spin A has only a small correlation ε with spin B, and B is only weakly correlated with C, but C is otherwise independent of A, the amount of correlation of A and C goes like ε2.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] For two spins separated by distance *L*, the amount of correlation goes as ε*L*, but if there is more than one path by which the correlations can travel, this amount is enhanced by the number of paths.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The number of paths of length *L* on a square lattice in *d* dimensions is $N(L)=(2d)^{L},$ since there are 2*d* choices for where to go at each step.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] A bound on the total correlation is given by the contribution to the correlation by summing over all paths linking two points, which is bounded above by the sum over all paths of length *L* divided by $\sum _{L}(2d)^{L}\varepsilon ^{L},$ which goes to zero when ε is small.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] At low temperatures (β ≫ 1) the configurations are near the lowest-energy configuration, the one where all the spins are plus or all the spins are minus.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Peierls asked whether it is statistically possible at low temperature, starting with all the spins minus, to fluctuate to a state where most of the spins are plus.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] For this to happen, droplets of plus spin must be able to congeal to make the plus state.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The energy of a droplet of plus spins in a minus background is proportional to the perimeter of the droplet L, where plus spins and minus spins neighbor each other.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] For a droplet with perimeter *L*, the area is somewhere between (*L* − 2)/2 (the straight line) and (*L*/4)2 (the square box).
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] For β sufficiently large, this exponentially suppresses long loops, so that they cannot occur, and the magnetization never fluctuates too far from −1.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] So Peierls established that the magnetization in the Ising model eventually defines superselection sectors, separated domains not linked by finite fluctuations.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Kramers and Wannier were able to show that the high-temperature expansion and the low-temperature expansion of the model are equal up to an overall rescaling of the free energy.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This allowed the phase-transition point in the two-dimensional model to be determined exactly (under the assumption that there is a unique critical point).
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] After Onsager's solution, Yang and Lee investigated the way in which the partition function becomes singular as the temperature approaches the critical temperature.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The original motivation for the model was the phenomenon of ferromagnetism.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Iron is magnetic; once it is magnetized it stays magnetized for a long time compared to any atomic time.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] In the 19th century, it was thought that magnetic fields are due to currents in matter, and Ampère postulated that permanent magnets are caused by permanent atomic currents.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The motion of classical charged particles could not explain permanent currents though, as shown by Larmor.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] In order to have ferromagnetism, the atoms must have permanent magnetic moments which are not due to the motion of classical charges.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Once the electron's spin was discovered, it was clear that the magnetism should be due to a large number of electron spins all oriented in the same direction.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] It was natural to ask how the electrons' spins all know which direction to point in, because the electrons on one side of a magnet don't directly interact with the electrons on the other side.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] They can only influence their neighbors.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The Ising model was designed to investigate whether a large fraction of the electron spins could be oriented in the same direction using only local forces.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The Ising model can be reinterpreted as a statistical model for the motion of atoms.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Since the kinetic energy depends only on momentum and not on position, while the statistics of the positions only depends on the potential energy, the thermodynamics of the gas only depends on the potential energy for each configuration of atoms.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] A coarse model is to make space-time a lattice and imagine that each position either contains an atom or it doesn't.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The space of configuration is that of independent bits *Bi*, where each bit is either 0 or 1 depending on whether the position is occupied or not.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] An attractive interaction reduces the energy of two nearby atoms.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] If the attraction is only between nearest neighbors, the energy is reduced by −4*JB**i**B**j* for each occupied neighboring pair.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The density of the atoms can be controlled by adding a chemical potential, which is a multiplicative probability cost for adding one more atom.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] A multiplicative factor in probability can be reinterpreted as an additive term in the logarithm – the energy.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The extra energy of a configuration with *N* atoms is changed by *μN*.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The probability cost of one more atom is a factor of exp(−*βμ*).
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] For lattices where every site has an equal number of neighbors, this is the Ising model with a magnetic field *h* = (*zJ* − *μ*)/2, where *z* is the number of neighbors.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] In biological systems, modified versions of the lattice gas model have been used to understand a range of binding behaviors.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] These include the binding of ligands to receptors in the cell surface, the binding of chemotaxis proteins to the flagellar motor, and the condensation of DNA.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The activity of neurons in the brain can be modelled statistically.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Each neuron at any time is either active + or inactive −.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The active neurons are those that send an action potential down the axon in any given time window, and the inactive ones are those that do not.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Following the general approach of Jaynes, a later interpretation of Schneidman, Berry, Segev and Bialek, is that the Ising model is useful for any model of neural function, because a statistical model for neural activity should be chosen using the principle of maximum entropy.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Given a collection of neurons, a statistical model which can reproduce the average firing rate for each neuron introduces a Lagrange multiplier for each neuron: $E=-\sum _{i}h_{i}S_{i}$ But the activity of each neuron in this model is statistically independent.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] To allow for pair correlations, when one neuron tends to fire (or not to fire) along with another, introduce pair-wise lagrange multipliers: $E=-{\tfrac {1}{2}}\sum _{ij}J_{ij}S_{i}S_{j}-\sum _{i}h_{i}S_{i}$ where $J_{ij}$ are not restricted to neighbors.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Note that this generalization of Ising model is sometimes called the quadratic exponential binary distribution in statistics.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This energy function only introduces probability biases for a spin having a value and for a pair of spins having the same value.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Higher order correlations are unconstrained by the multipliers.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] An activity pattern sampled from this distribution requires the largest number of bits to store in a computer, in the most efficient coding scheme imaginable, as compared with any other distribution with the same average activity and pairwise correlations.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This means that Ising models are relevant to any system which is described by bits which are as random as possible, with constraints on the pairwise correlations and the average number of 1s, which frequently occurs in both the physical and social sciences.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] With the Ising model the so-called spin glasses can also be described, by the usual Hamiltonian ${\textstyle H=-{\frac {1}{2}}\,\sum J_{i,k}\,S_{i}\,S_{k},}$ where the *S*-variables describe the Ising spins, while the *Ji,k* are taken from a random distribution.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] For spin glasses a typical distribution chooses antiferromagnetic bonds with probability *p* and ferromagnetic bonds with probability 1 − *p* (also known as the random-bond Ising model).
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] These bonds stay fixed or "quenched" even in the presence of thermal fluctuations.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] When *p* = 0 we have the original Ising model.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This system deserves interest in its own; particularly one has "non-ergodic" properties leading to strange relaxation behaviour.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Much attention has been also attracted by the related bond and site dilute Ising model, especially in two dimensions, leading to intriguing critical behavior.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The Ising model was instrumental in the development of the Hopfield network.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The original Ising model is a model for equilibrium.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Glauber in 1963 studied the Ising model evolving in time, as a process towards thermal equilibrium (Glauber dynamics), adding in the component of time.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] (Kaoru Nakano, 1971) and (Shun'ichi Amari, 1972), proposed to modify the weights of an Ising model by Hebbian learning rule as a model of associative memory.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The same idea was published by (William A.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Little, 1974), who was cited by Hopfield in his 1982 paper.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The Sherrington–Kirkpatrick model of spin glass, published in 1975, is the Hopfield network with random initialization.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Sherrington and Kirkpatrick found that it is highly likely for the energy function of the SK model to have many local minima.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] In the 1982 paper, Hopfield applied this recently developed theory to study the Hopfield network with binary activation functions.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] In a 1984 paper he extended this to continuous activation functions.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] It became a standard model for the study of neural networks through statistical mechanics.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The melt pond can be modelled by the Ising model; sea ice topography data bears rather heavily on the results.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The state variable is binary for a simple 2D approximation, being either water or ice.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The spin-spin correlation between sites (in general, m and n) on the tree was found to have a transition point when considered at the vertices (e.g.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] A and Ā, its reflection), their respective neighboring sites (such as B and its reflection), and between sites adjacent to the top and bottom extreme vertices of the two trees (e.g.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The model's behavior is also of relevance for any other divergent-convergent tree physical (or biological) system exhibiting a closed Cayley tree topology with an Ising-type of interaction.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This topology should not be ignored since its behavior for Ising models has been solved exactly, and presumably nature will have found a way of taking advantage of such simple symmetries at many levels of its designs.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] It was a natural and common belief among early neurophysicists (e.g.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The Ising model can often be difficult to evaluate numerically if there are many states in the system.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Since every spin site has ±1 spin, there are *2**L* different states that are possible.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This motivates the reason for the Ising model to be simulated using Monte Carlo methods.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Furthermore, the Hamiltonian is further simplified by assuming zero external field *h*, since many questions that are posed to be solved using the model can be answered in absence of an external field.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Given this Hamiltonian, quantities of interest such as the specific heat or the magnetization of the magnet at a given temperature can be calculated.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm is the most commonly used Monte Carlo algorithm to calculate Ising model estimations.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The algorithm first chooses *selection probabilities* *g*(μ, ν), which represent the probability that state ν is selected by the algorithm out of all states, given that one is in state μ.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] It then uses acceptance probabilities *A*(μ, ν) so that detailed balance is satisfied.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] If the new state ν is accepted, then we move to that state and repeat with selecting a new state and deciding to accept it.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This process is repeated until some stopping criterion is met, which for the Ising model is often when the lattice becomes ferromagnetic, meaning all of the sites point in the same direction.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] When implementing the algorithm, one must ensure that *g*(μ, ν) is selected such that ergodicity is met.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] In thermal equilibrium a system's energy only fluctuates within a small range.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This is the motivation behind the concept of **single-spin-flip dynamics**, which states that in each transition, we will only change one of the spin sites on the lattice.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Furthermore, by using single- spin-flip dynamics, one can get from any state to any other state by flipping each site that differs between the two states one at a time.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The maximum amount of change between the energy of the present state, *H*μ and any possible new state's energy *H*ν (using single-spin-flip dynamics) is 2*J* between the spin we choose to "flip" to move to the new state and that spin's neighbor.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Thus, in a 1D Ising model, where each site has two neighbors (left and right), the maximum difference in energy would be 4*J*.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Let *c* represent the *lattice coordination number*; the number of nearest neighbors that any lattice site has.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] We assume that all sites have the same number of neighbors due to periodic boundary conditions.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] It is important to note that the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm does not perform well around the critical point due to critical slowing down.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Other techniques such as multigrid methods, Niedermayer's algorithm, Swendsen–Wang algorithm, or the Wolff algorithm are required in order to resolve the model near the critical point; a requirement for determining the critical exponents of the system.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Specifically for the Ising model and using single-spin-flip dynamics, one can establish the following.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Since there are *L* total sites on the lattice, using single-spin-flip as the only way we transition to another state, we can see that there are a total of *L* new states ν from our present state μ.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The algorithm assumes that the selection probabilities are equal to the *L* states: *g*(μ, ν) = 1/*L*.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Metropolis sets the larger of *A*(μ, ν) or *A*(ν, μ) to be 1.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Flip the value of the spin and calculate the new contribution.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] If the new energy is less, keep the flipped value.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] The change in energy *H*ν − *H*μ only depends on the value of the spin and its nearest graph neighbors.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] So if the graph is not too connected, the algorithm is fast.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] This process will eventually produce a pick from the distribution.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] It is possible to view the Ising model as a Markov chain, as the immediate probability *P*β(ν) of transitioning to a future state ν only depends on the present state μ.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p01] Furthermore, since the energy equation *H*σ change only depends on the nearest-neighbor interaction strength *J*, the Ising model and its variants such the Sznajd model can be seen as a form of a voter model for opinion dynamics.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The thermodynamic limit exists as long as the interaction decay is $J_{ij}\sim |i-j|^{-\alpha }$ with α > 1.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] In the nearest neighbor case (with periodic or free boundary conditions) an exact solution is available.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] For *T* → 0, though, the inverse correlation length *c*(β) vanishes.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The proof of this result is a simple computation.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] hence it decays exponentially as soon as *T* ≠ 0; but for *T* = 0, i.e. in the limit β → ∞ there is no decay.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] If *h* ≠ 0 we need the transfer matrix method.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] For the periodic boundary conditions case is the following.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] This gives the formula of the free energy above.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] In the thermodynamics limit for the non-interaction case (J = 0), we got $Z_{N}\to (\lambda _{1})^{N}=(2\cosh \beta h)^{N},$ as the answer for the open-boundary Ising model.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The energy of the lowest state is −*JL*, when all the spins are the same.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] For any other configuration, the extra energy is equal to 2*J* times the number of sign changes that are encountered when scanning the configuration from left to right.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] If we designate the number of sign changes in a configuration as *k*, the difference in energy from the lowest energy state is 2*k*.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] Since the energy is additive in the number of flips, the probability *p* of having a spin-flip at each position is independent.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The problem is reduced to independent biased coin tosses.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] This essentially completes the mathematical description.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] From the description in terms of independent tosses, the statistics of the model for long lines can be understood.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] Each domain is of average length exp(2β).
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The length of a domain is distributed exponentially, since there is a constant probability at any step of encountering a flip.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The domains never become infinite, so a long system is never magnetized.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] Each step reduces the correlation between a spin and its neighbor by an amount proportional to *p*, so the correlations fall off exponentially.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The partition function is the volume of configurations, each configuration weighted by its Boltzmann weight.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] A sign of a phase transition is a non-analytic free energy, so the one-dimensional model does not have a phase transition.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] To express the Ising Hamiltonian using a quantum mechanical description of spins, we replace the spin variables with their respective Pauli matrices.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] However, depending on the direction of the magnetic field, we can create a transverse-field or longitudinal-field Hamiltonian.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The transverse-field model experiences a phase transition between an ordered and disordered regime at *J* ~ *h*.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] Since the roles of *h* and *J* are switched, the Hamiltonian undergoes a transition at *J* = *h*.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] When there is no external field, we can derive a functional equation that $f(\beta ,0)=f(\beta )$ satisfies using renormalization.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] Specifically, let $Z_{N}(\beta ,J)$ be the partition function with N sites.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] When $\beta$ is small, we have $f(\beta )\approx \ln 2$ , so we can numerically evaluate $f(\beta )$ by iterating the functional equation until K is small.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] In the ferromagnetic case there is a phase transition.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] At low temperature, the Peierls argument proves positive magnetization for the nearest neighbor case and then, by the Griffiths inequality, also when longer range interactions are added.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] Meanwhile, at high temperature, the cluster expansion gives analyticity of the thermodynamic functions.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] In the nearest-neighbor case, the free energy was exactly computed by Onsager.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The spin-spin correlation functions were computed by McCoy and Wu.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] From this expression for the free energy, all thermodynamic functions of the model can be calculated by using an appropriate derivative.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The 2D Ising model was the first model to exhibit a continuous phase transition at a positive temperature.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] When the interaction energies $J_{1}$ , $J_{2}$ are both negative, the Ising model becomes an antiferromagnet.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] Since the square lattice is bi-partite, it is invariant under this change when the magnetic field $h=0$ , so the free energy and critical temperature are the same for the antiferromagnetic case.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] For the triangular lattice, which is not bi-partite, the ferromagnetic and antiferromagnetic Ising model behave notably differently.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] Specifically, around a triangle, it is impossible to make all 3 spin-pairs antiparallel, so the antiferromagnetic Ising model cannot reach the minimal energy state.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] This is an example of geometric frustration.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] where $J_{1}$ and $J_{2}$ are horizontal and vertical interaction energies.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] A complete derivation was only given in 1951 by Yang (1952) using a limiting process of transfer matrix eigenvalues.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The proof was subsequently greatly simplified in 1963 by Montroll, Potts, and Ward using Szegő's limit formula for Toeplitz determinants by treating the magnetization as the limit of correlation functions.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] At the critical point, the two-dimensional Ising model is a two-dimensional conformal field theory.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The spin and energy correlation functions are described by a minimal model, which has been exactly solved.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] In three as in two dimensions, the most studied case of the Ising model is the translation-invariant model on a cubic lattice with nearest-neighbor coupling in the zero magnetic field.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] Many theoreticians searched for an analytical three-dimensional solution for many decades, which would be analogous to Onsager's solution in the two-dimensional case.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] Such a solution has not been found until now, although there is no proof that it may not exist.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] In three dimensions, the Ising model was shown to have a representation in terms of non-interacting fermionic strings by Alexander Polyakov and Vladimir Dotsenko.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] This construction has been carried on the lattice, and the continuum limit, conjecturally describing the critical point, is unknown.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] In three as in two dimensions, Peierls' argument shows that there is a phase transition.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] This phase transition is rigorously known to be continuous (in the sense that correlation length diverges and the magnetization goes to zero), and is called the critical point.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] It is believed that the critical point can be described by a renormalization group fixed point of the Wilson-Kadanoff renormalization group transformation.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] It is also believed that the phase transition can be described by a three-dimensional unitary conformal field theory, as evidenced by Monte Carlo simulations, exact diagonalization results in quantum models, and quantum field theoretical arguments.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] This conformal field theory describing the three-dimensional Ising critical point is under active investigation using the method of the conformal bootstrap.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] This method currently yields the most precise information about the structure of the critical theory (see Ising critical exponents).
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] In 2000, Sorin Istrail of Sandia National Laboratories proved that the spin glass Ising model on a nonplanar lattice is NP-complete.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] That is, assuming **P** ≠ **NP,** the general spin glass Ising model is exactly solvable only in planar cases, so solutions for dimensions higher than two are also intractable.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] Istrail's result only concerns the spin glass model with spatially varying couplings, and tells nothing about Ising's original ferromagnetic model with equal couplings.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] In any dimension, the Ising model can be productively described by a locally varying mean field.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The field is defined as the average spin value over a large region, but not so large so as to include the entire system.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The field still has slow variations from point to point, as the averaging volume moves.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] These fluctuations in the field are described by a continuum field theory in the infinite system limit.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] The accuracy of this approximation improves as the dimension becomes larger.
[src:critical-phenomena/ising-model-p02] A deeper understanding of how the Ising model behaves, going beyond mean-field approximations, can be achieved using renormalization group methods.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] In theoretical physics, the **renormalization group** (**RG**) is a mathematical tool that allows systematic investigation into the changes in a physical system as it is viewed at different scales.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The scales of the system typically describe the interactions of the objects; they may be variable ("running") couplings which measure the strength of various forces, mass parameters, or the size of the system.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] In particle physics, this treatment reflects the changes in the underlying physical laws (codified in a quantum field theory that is renormalizable) as the energy or mass scale at which physical processes occur varies.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] For example, in quantum electrodynamics (QED), an electron appears to be composed of electron and positron pairs and photons at very short distances.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Taken together, this set of particles has a slightly different electric charge than the dressed electron seen at large distances, and this change in the value of the charge is determined by the renormalization group equation.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The renormalization group was initially developed for particle physics applications but has since been applied to solid-state physics, fluid mechanics, physical cosmology, and nanotechnology.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Low restricted the idea to scale transformations in QED in 1954 and focused on asymptotic forms of the photon propagator at high energies.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] More formally, this transformation is described mathematically by Schröder's equation.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] On the basis of this finite group equation and its scaling property, Gell-Mann and Low focused on infinitesimal transformations, and invented a computational method based on the function *ψ*(*g*) = *G* *d*/(∂*G*/∂*g*) which they introduced.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Since it is a function of *g*, integration in *g* of a perturbative estimate of it permits specification of the variation of the function with energy - effectively the function *G* in this approximation.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The renormalization group prediction was confirmed 40 years later at the Large Electron–Positron Collider experiments: the fine structure "constant" of QED was measured to be about 1⁄127 at energies close to 200 GeV, as opposed to the standard low-energy physics value of 1⁄137.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The renormalization group emerges from the renormalization of the quantum field variables, which has to address the problem of infinite terms in a quantum field theory.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The process for doing this systematically for QED was created by Richard Feynman, Julian Schwinger and Shin'ichirō Tomonaga, who received the 1965 Nobel prize for these contributions.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] They devised the theory of mass and charge renormalization, in which the infinity in the momentum scale is cut off by an ultra-large regulator, Λ.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The dependence of physical quantities on the scale Λ is hidden, effectively swapped for the longer-distance scales at which the physical quantities are measured; as a result, all observable quantities are finite even for an infinite Λ.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Gell-Mann and Low thus realized in these results that, while a tiny change in*g* is provided by the above RG equation given ψ(*g*), the self-similarity is expressed by the fact that ψ(*g*) depends explicitly only upon the parameters of the theory, and not upon the scale *μ*.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Consequently, the above renormalization group equation may be solved for (*G* and thus) *g*(*μ*).
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] A deeper understanding of the physical meaning and generalization of the renormalization process, which goes beyond the dilation group of conventional renormalizable theories, considers methods where widely different scales appear simultaneously.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] It came from condensed matter physics: Leo P.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Kadanoff's paper in 1966 proposed the "block-spin" renormalization group.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The "blocking idea" is a way to define the components of the theory at large distances as aggregates of components at shorter distances.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] This approach covered the conceptual point and was given full computational substance in the work of Kenneth Wilson.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Wilson demonstrated a constructive iterative renormalization solution of a long-standing problem, the Kondo problem, in 1975, as well as the preceding seminal developments of his new method in the theory of second-order phase transitions and critical phenomena in 1971.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] He was awarded the Nobel prize for these contributions in 1982.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The RG in particle physics was reformulated in more practical terms by Callan and Symanzik in 1970.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The above beta function, which describes the "running of the coupling" parameter with scale, was found to represent the quantum-mechanical breaking of scale symmetry in a field theory.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Applications of the RG to particle physics sharply increased in number in the 1970s with the establishment of the Standard Model.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] In 1973, it was discovered that a theory of interacting quarks had a negative beta function.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] This means that an initial high-energy value of the coupling will eventuate a special value of μ at which the coupling diverges.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] This special value is the scale of the strong interactions, μ = ΛQCD (~200 mega-electronvolts).
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Conversely, the coupling becomes weak at very high energies (asymptotic freedom), and the quarks become observable as point-like particles, in deep inelastic scattering, as anticipated by Feynman–Bjorken scaling.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] QCD was thereby established as the quantum field theory controlling the strong interactions of particles.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Momentum space RG also became a highly developed tool in solid state physics, but was hindered by the extensive use of perturbation theory, which prevented the theory from succeeding in strongly correlated systems.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] A generic theory is described by a certain function Z of the state variables $\{s_{i}\}$ and a certain set of coupling constants $\{J_{k}\}$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] This function may be a partition function, an action, a Hamiltonian, so long as it contains the whole description of the physics of the system.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] For a certain transformation of the state variables $\{s_{i}\}\to \{{\tilde {s}}_{i}\}$ , the number of ${\tilde {s}}_{i}$ is less than the number of $s_{i}$ .
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] If the Z function can be rewritten only in terms of the ${\tilde {s}}_{i}$ by a certain change in the parameters, $\{J_{k}\}\to \{{\tilde {J}}_{k}\}$ , then the theory is said to be renormalizable.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The change in the parameters is implemented by a certain beta function: $\{{\tilde {J}}_{k}\}=\beta (\{J_{k}\})$ , which is said to induce a renormalization group flow (or RG flow) on the J -space.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The values of J under the flow are called running couplings.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Most fundamental theories of physics with the exception of gravity are exactly renormalizable.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Similarly, most theories in condensed matter physics are approximately renormalizable.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Conformal symmetry is associated with the vanishing of the beta function.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] This can occur naturally if a coupling constant is attracted, by running, toward a fixed point at which *β*(*g*) = 0.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] In QCD, the fixed point occurs at short distances where *g* → 0 and is called a (trivial) ultraviolet fixed point.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] In string theory, conformal invariance of the string world-sheet is a fundamental symmetry: *β* = 0 is a requirement.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Here, *β* is a function of the geometry of the space-time in which the string moves.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] This determines the space-time dimensionality of the string theory and enforces Einstein's equations of general relativity on the geometry.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The RG is of fundamental importance to string theory and theories of grand unification.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] If the fixed points of the system correspond to a free field theory, the theory is said to exhibit quantum triviality and possesses a Landau pole.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] For a φ4 interaction, Michael Aizenman proved that this theory is indeed trivial, for space-time dimension D ≥ 5.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] For D = 4, the triviality has yet to be proven rigorously, but lattice computations have provided strong evidence for this.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] This fact is important as quantum triviality can be used to bound or even predict parameters such as the Higgs boson mass in asymptotic safety scenarios.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Numerous fixed points appear in the study of lattice Higgs theories, but the nature of the quantum field theories associated with these remains an open question.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Since the RG transformations in such systems are lossy (i.e. the number of variables decreases), there need not be an inverse for a given RG transformation.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] A relevant observable is needed to describe the macroscopic behavior of the system; irrelevant observables are not needed.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Marginal observables may or may not need to be taken into account.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Most observables are irrelevant, i.e., the macroscopic physics is dominated by only a few observables in most systems.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] As an example, in microscopic physics, to describe a system consisting of a mole of carbon-12 atoms we need of the order of 1023 (the Avogadro number) variables, while to describe it as a macroscopic system (12 grams of carbon-12) we only need a few.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Before Wilson's RG approach, it was unclear why the critical exponents describing transitions in very disparate phenomena.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] In general, thermodynamic features of a system near a phase transition depend only on a small number of variables, such as the dimensionality and symmetry, but are insensitive to details of the underlying microscopic properties of the system.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Universality can be explained using the renormalization group, by demonstrating that the differences in phenomena among the individual fine-scale components are determined by irrelevant observables, while the relevant observables are shared in common.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Therefore, many macroscopic phenomena may be grouped into a small set of universality classes, specified by the shared sets of relevant observables.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] One of the simpler forms of RG is the block spin RG, devised by Leo P.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] For a 2D set of atoms in a perfect square array (Figure 1), atoms interact among themselves only with their nearest neighbors at some temperature T and a certain coupling J.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The physics of the system is then described by a certain function of these parameters, such as the Hamiltonian *H*(*T*, *J*).
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The solid is then divided into blocks of 2×2 blocks*,* described in terms of block variables that represent the average behavior within each block.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The physics of block variables is approximately described by a formula of the same kind, but with different values for T and J: *H*(*T′*, *J′*).
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The original problem may be computationally intractable due to the large number of atomic variables involved; in the renormalized problem, there are one fourth as many.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Another iteration of the same kind leads to *H*(*T"*, *J"*), and only one sixteenth of the atoms.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] This process increases the observation scale with each RG step.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Iterating until there is only one large block is roughly equivalent to finding the long range behavior of the RG transformation which took (*T*,*J*) → (*T′*,*J′*) and (*T′*, *J′*) → (*T"*, *J"*).
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Often, when iterated many times, this RG transformation leads to a certain number of fixed points.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] For the test case of an Ising model lattice of spins interacting magnetically, some positive coupling J denotes the trend of neighbor spins to be aligned.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The behavior of the system is determined by competition between the J term (which tends to "order" the system by aligning spins) and the disordering effect of temperature, which the alignment of spins to vary randomly.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Temperature dominates, and the system is disordered at large scales.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] A nontrivial point between them, *T* = *T**c* and *J* = *J**c*.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] At this point, changing the scale does not change the physics, because the system will look the same at any choice of scales.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] This corresponds to the critical point of the Curie phase transition, where the two effects above are perfectly balanced.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Given a certain material with given values of T and J, the large-scale behavior of the system is then determined by these fixed points.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] An exact renormalization group equation (ERGE) is one that takes irrelevant couplings into account.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] As there are infinitely many choices of field rescalings, there are also infinitely many different interpolating ERGEs, but the most common approaches are presented below.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The Wilson ERGE is the simplest conceptually, but is difficult to implement.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The method begins with a Fourier transform into momentum space after Wick rotating into Euclidean space.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] By setting a hard momentum cutoff, *p*2 ≤ Λ2, the only degrees of freedom are those with momenta less than Λ.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] If you compute *S*Λ′ from *S*Λ and then compute *SΛ′′* from *S*Λ′, this gives you the same Wilsonian action as computing *S*Λ″ directly from *S*Λ.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The Polchinski ERGE involves a smooth UV regulator cutoff,an improvement over the Wilson ERGE.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] This suppresses contributions from momenta greater than Λ heavily.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The smoothness of the cutoff, however, generates a functional differential equation in the cutoff scale Λ.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] As in Wilson's approach, there is a different action functional for each Λ.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Each of these actions are supposed to describe exactly the same model - which means that their partition functionals have to match exactly.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The action is split into a quadratic kinetic part and an interacting part *S*int Λ.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] This split is not clean generically; the "interacting" part can also contain quadratic kinetic terms and if there is any wave function renormalization, it must.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] This can be reduced by introducing field rescalings.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] RΛ is a function of the momentum p and the second term in the exponent is ${\frac {1}{2}}\int {\frac {d^{d}p}{(2\pi )^{d}}}{\tilde {\varphi }}^{*}(p)R_{\Lambda }(p){\tilde {\varphi }}(p)$ when expanded.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] *R*Λ(*p*)/*p*2 is always greater than or equal to 1 and is smooth.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] This leaves the fluctuations with momenta less than the cutoff Λ unaffected but heavily suppresses contributions from those with momenta greater than the cutoff.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The effective average action ERGE involves a smooth IR regulator cutoff, which accounts for all fluctuations up to an IR scale k.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The effective average action (EAA) will be accurate for fluctuations with momenta larger than k.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] As k is lowered, the effective average action approaches the effective action which includes all quantum and classical fluctuations.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] In contrast, for large k the effective average action is close to the "bare action".
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] So, the effective average action interpolates between the "bare action" and the effective action.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Its large value for small momenta leads to a suppression of their contribution to the partition function which is effectively the same thing as neglecting large-scale fluctuations.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The Legendre transform of *W**k* ordinarily gives the effective action.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] However, the initial action is in fact *S*[*φ*] + 1/2 *φ⋅R**k*⋅*φ* and so the second term must be subtracted to get the effective average action.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] Taking a derivative with respect to the cutoff completes the process, producing an expression known as the Wetterich equation.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] The renormalization group can also be used to compute effective potentials at orders higher than 1-loop, such as when computing corrections to the Coleman–Weinberg mechanism.
[src:critical-phenomena/renormalization-group] To do so, write the renormalization group equation in terms of the effective potential.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] In statistical mechanics, **universality** is the observation that there are properties for a large class of systems that are independent of the dynamical details of the system.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] Systems display universality in a scaling limit, when a large number of interacting parts come together.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The modern meaning of the term was introduced by Leo Kadanoff in the 1960s, but a simpler version of the concept was already implicit in the van der Waals equation and in the earlier Landau theory of phase transitions, which did not incorporate scaling correctly.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The renormalization group provides an intuitively appealing, albeit mathematically non-rigorous, explanation of universality.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] It classifies operators in a statistical field theory into relevant and irrelevant.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] Relevant operators are those responsible for perturbations to the free energy (analagously the Lagrangian in quantum field theory) that will affect the continuum limit, and can be seen at long distances.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] Irrelevant operators are those that only change the short-distance details.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The collection of scale-invariant statistical theories define the universality classes, and the finite-dimensional list of coefficients of relevant operators parametrize the near-critical behavior.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The notion of universality originated in the study of phase transitions in statistical mechanics.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] A phase transition occurs when a material changes its properties in a dramatic way: water, as it is heated boils and turns into vapor; or a magnet, when heated, loses its magnetism.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] Phase transitions are characterized by an order parameter, such as the density or the magnetization, that changes as a function of a parameter of the system, such as the temperature.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The special value of the parameter at which the system changes its phase is the system's critical point.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] For systems that exhibit universality, the closer the parameter is to its **critical value**, the less sensitively the order parameter depends on the details of the system.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The exponent α is a critical exponent of the system.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The remarkable discovery made in the second half of the twentieth century was that very different systems had the same critical exponents .
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] In 1975, Mitchell Feigenbaum discovered universality in iterated maps.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] Universality gets its name because it is seen in a large variety of physical systems.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] One of the important developments in materials science in the 1970s and the 1980s was the realization that statistical field theory, similar to quantum field theory, could be used to provide a microscopic theory of universality .
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The core observation was that, for all of the different systems, the behaviour at a phase transition is described by a continuum field, and that the same statistical field theory will describe different systems.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The scaling exponents in all of these systems can be derived from the field theory alone, and are known as critical exponents.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] Universality is a by-product of the fact that there are relatively few scale-invariant theories.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] For any one specific physical system, the detailed description may have many scale-dependent parameters and aspects.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] However, as the phase transition is approached, the scale-dependent parameters play less and less of an important role, and the scale-invariant parts of the physical description dominate.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] Thus, a simplified, and often exactly solvable, model can be used to approximate the behaviour of these systems near the critical point.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] Percolation may be modeled by a random electrical resistor network, with electricity flowing from one side of the network to the other.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The overall resistance of the network is seen to be described by the average connectivity of the resistors in the network .
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The formation of tears and cracks may be modeled by a random network of electrical fuses.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] As the electric current flow through the network is increased, some fuses may pop, but on the whole, the current is shunted around the problem areas, and uniformly distributed.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] However, at a certain point (at the phase transition) a cascade failure may occur, where the excess current from one popped fuse overloads the next fuse in turn, until the two sides of the net are completely disconnected and no more current flows .
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] To perform the analysis of such random-network systems, one considers the stochastic space of all possible networks (that is, the canonical ensemble), and performs a summation (integration) over all possible network configurations.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] As in the previous discussion, each given random configuration is understood to be drawn from the pool of all configurations with some given probability distribution; the role of temperature in the distribution is typically replaced by the average connectivity of the network .
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The expectation values of operators, such as the rate of flow, the heat capacity, and so on, are obtained by integrating over all possible configurations.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] This act of integration over all possible configurations is the point of commonality between systems in statistical mechanics and quantum field theory.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] In particular, the language of the renormalization group may be applied to the discussion of the random network models.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] In the 1990s and 2000s, stronger connections between the statistical models and conformal field theory were uncovered.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The study of universality remains a vital area of research.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] Like other concepts from statistical mechanics (such as entropy and master equations), universality has proven a useful construct for characterizing distributed systems at a higher level, such as multi-agent systems.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] The term has been applied to multi-agent simulations, where the system-level behavior exhibited by the system is independent of the degree of complexity of the individual agents, being driven almost entirely by the nature of the constraints governing their interactions.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] In network dynamics, universality refers to the fact that despite the diversity of nonlinear dynamic models, which differ in many details, the observed behavior of many different systems adheres to a set of universal laws.
[src:critical-phenomena/universality-dynamical-systems] These laws are independent of the specific details of each system.
[src:critical-phenomena/widom-scaling] Widom scaling is an example of universality.
[src:critical-phenomena/widom-scaling] measures the temperature relative to the critical point.
[src:critical-phenomena/widom-scaling] with $\omega$ being Wegner's exponent governing the approach to scaling.
[src:critical-phenomena/widom-scaling] The relations are experimentally well verified for magnetic systems and fluids.
